The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Thiruvananthapuram: A police officer probing a mid-air molestation charge against a minister in Kerala is learnt to have recommended registering a case against him for a formal investigation, reports our special correspondent.

 If the government accepts the recommendation, public works minister P.J. Joseph will have little option but to step aside during the police investigation.

 spector-general of police B. Sandhya submitted her report to home secretary Lizzie Jacob here on Sunday.

 Lekshmi Gopakumar, a former news anchor with Surya TV, and her husband had alleged on several occasions, both on and off camera, that Joseph, who occupied the wrong seat behind her, touched her as a Kingfisher flight took off from Chennai for Kochi on August 3.

 Chandigarh (PTI): The CBI has registered a case against 19 people, including seven IPS officers, and three private companies for alleged cheating and forgery in the purchase of wireless sets by Punjab police. From 2000 to 2003, officers of the communication and wireless wing of Punjab police allegedly connived with the companies to embezzle funds exceeding Rs 5 crore to buy substandard sets. 

 Kanpur (PTI): The Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur is organising health workshops to help its students cope with tension caused by high expectations, tough competition and the pressure to succeed. 

 Akola (PTI): Three girls drowned in the Mas river after they were caught in a whirlpool at a village in Maharashtras Buldhana district, police said on Sunday.




